-- ########## ENGLISH ARTICLES (5) ##########
(gen_random_uuid(), 
 'Climate-Resilient Agriculture: Adapting to Changing Weather', 
 'Strategies for farmers to maintain yield despite unpredictable rainfall and heatwaves.', 
 'Climate change is the biggest challenge for modern Indian agriculture. To combat this, farmers must adopt climate-resilient practices: \n\n1. Heat-Tolerant Varieties: Use seeds like HD 2967 (Wheat) that withstand terminal heat. \n2. Mulching Techniques: Cover soil with crop residues to prevent moisture evaporation and regulate soil temperature. \n3. Rainwater Harvesting: Constructing farm ponds or "Shet-Tali" to store excess monsoon water for the Rabi season. \n4. Integrated Farming: Combine crops with livestock to diversify income sources and reduce risk from crop failure. \n5. Weather-Based Advisories: Using mobile apps to get real-time alerts on storms and frost. This proactive approach ensures food security even in adverse conditions.', 
 'climate-smart', 'Dr. S. Swaminathan', 12, 'English', 'internal', true, true, 'ЁЯМбя╕П'),

(gen_random_uuid(), 
 'Advanced Hydroponics: Farming Without Soil', 
 'A deep dive into soilless culture and vertical farming for high-value crops.', 
 'Hydroponics is gaining traction in urban-adjacent areas for growing leafy greens like lettuce, basil, and spinach. \n\nSystems Explained:\n- Nutrient Film Technique (NFT): A thin film of nutrient-rich water flows over the roots.\n- Deep Water Culture (DWC): Plants float on a reservoir of oxygenated nutrient solution.\n- Aeroponics: Roots are suspended in air and misted with nutrients. \n\nKey Advantages: Hydroponics uses 90% less water than traditional farming, eliminates soil-borne diseases, and allows for year-round production in controlled environments (Greenhouses). However, it requires a constant electricity supply and precise monitoring of pH (5.5-6.5) and EC (Electrical Conductivity).', 
 'agri-tech', 'Urban Farm Specialist', 15, 'English', 'internal', true, false, 'ЁЯем'),

(gen_random_uuid(), 
 'Post-Harvest Management and Cold Chain Logistics', 
 'How to reduce wastage and increase shelf life of perishable produce.', 
 'In India, nearly 20-30% of fruits and vegetables are wasted due to poor post-harvest handling. \n\nCritical Steps:\n1. Pre-cooling: Removing field heat immediately after harvest significantly slows down decay.\n2. Sorting and Grading: Grouping produce by size and quality to fetch better market prices.\n3. Modified Atmosphere Packaging (MAP): Using specific gases to extend freshness.\n4. Cold Storage: Maintaining temperatures between 0┬░C to 4┬░C for temperate fruits. \n\nBy investing in small-scale pack-houses and solar-powered cold storages, farmers can bypass middlemen and sell directly to retail chains when prices are favorable.', 
 'post-harvest', 'Logistics Expert', 10, 'English', 'internal', true, false, 'тЭДя╕П'),

(gen_random_uuid(), 
 'The Role of Drones in Precision Spraying and Mapping', 
 'Utilizing UAV technology for efficient pesticide application and crop health monitoring.', 
 'Agricultural drones (UAVs) are revolutionizing how we view large-scale farming. \n\n- Precision Spraying: Drones can spray 1 acre in just 10-15 minutes, using 70% less water and 20% less chemicals compared to manual spraying. \n- Multispectral Imaging: Drones equipped with special cameras can detect "invisible" plant stress (lack of nitrogen or water) before the human eye can see it. \n- Safety: Drones keep farmers away from toxic chemical exposure. \n\nRegulatory Note: Farmers must obtain a UIN (Unique Identification Number) and follow DGCA guidelines for operating drones in rural zones. This technology is particularly useful for tall crops like Sugarcane and Orchards.', 
 'smart-farming', 'Tech-Agri Lead', 11, 'English', 'internal', true, true, 'ЁЯЪБ'),

(gen_random_uuid(), 
 'Financial Literacy for Farmers: Loans, Credit and Insurance', 
 'Understanding the banking system to fuel agricultural growth.', 
 'Capital is the fuel for farming. Understanding financial products is vital:\n\n1. Kisan Credit Card (KCC): Offers low-interest loans (as low as 4%) with timely repayment. It covers cultivation expenses and post-harvest requirements.\n2. Warehousing Receipts: Farmers can take loans against the stocks stored in recognized warehouses to avoid "distress sales."\n3. Micro-Finance: Smaller loans for SHGs (Self Help Groups) to start allied businesses like poultry or beekeeping.\n4. Interest Subvention: The government provides a 2% interest subsidy for short-term crop loans up to 3 Lakhs. \n\nMaintain a good CIBIL score by repaying loans on time to ensure easy access to future credit for buying tractors or land.', 
 'finance', 'Bank Mitra', 9, 'English', 'internal', true, false, 'ЁЯТ░'),

